%N A270109 a(n) = n^3 + (n+1)*(n+2).
%C A270109 For n>1, many consecutive terms of the sequence are generated by floor(sqrt(n^2 + 2)^3) + n^2 + 2.
%C A270109 It appears that this is a subsequence of A000037 (the nonsquares).
%C A270109 The primes in the sequence belong to A045326.
%C A270109 Inverse binomial transform is 2, 5, 8, 6, 0, 0, 0, ... (0 continued).
%H A270109 Bruno Berselli, <a href="/A270109/b270109.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..1000</a>
%H A270109 MathsSmart, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iMc3z8TvV8g">Number pattern and Puzzle - 7, 20, 47, 94, 167</a>.
%H A270109 <a href="/index/Rec#order_04">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (4,-6,4,-1).
%F A270109 O.g.f.: (2 - x + 4*x^2 + x^3)/(1 - x)^4.
%F A270109 E.g.f.: (2 + x)*(1 + x)^2*exp(x).
%F A270109 a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - 6*a(n-2) + 4*a(n-3) - a(n-4), n>3.
%F A270109 a(n+h) - a(n) + a(n-h) = n^3 + n^2 + (6*h^2+3)*n + (2*h^2+2) for any h. This identity becomes a(n) = n^3 + n^2 + 3*n + 2 if h=0.
%F A270109 a(h*a(n) + n) = (h*a(n))^3 + (3*n+1)*(h*a(n))^2 + (3*n^2+2*n+3)*(h*a(n)) + a(n) for any h, therefore a(h*a(n) + n) is always a multiple of a(n).
%F A270109 a(n) + a(-n) = 2*A059100(n) = A255843(n).
%F A270109 a(n) - a(-n) = 4*A229183(n).
%t A270109 Table[n^3 + (n + 1) (n + 2), {n, 0, 50}]
%o A270109 (PARI) vector(50, n, n--; n^3+(n+1)*(n+2))
%o A270109 (SageMath) [n^3+(n+1)*(n+2) for n in (0..50)]
